<TITLE> Iran minister resigns in new cabinet change </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TEHRAN, Dec 2 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Iran's education minister resigned on Sunday, heralding another change in President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad's cabinet before a parliamentary election in March. The education minister is in charge of thousands of teachers and some have protested this year about pay and conditions. During a no-confidence vote which Education Minister Mahmoud Farshidi survived this year, some MPs referred to the teachers' complaints. Ahmadinejad came to power in 2005 pledging to improve the lot of ordinary Iranians. Ahmadinejad accepted Farshidi's resignation at a cabinet meeting, Iran's state broadcaster said on its Web site. No reason was given for Farshidi's resignation. Ahmadinejad has sacked or changed other cabinet posts including his industries minister, replaced by a close ally, and the oil minister, whose position was taken by a technocrat. He has also replaced the central bank governor. "It appears that Ahmadinejad has decided in the remaining months (before the parliamentary polls) to have people in office who are obedient and very close to him," said an Iranian political analyst, who asked not to be identified. Farshidi's unpopularity with teachers might have made his presence in the cabinet a political liability in the election, the analyst sa
